            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "David Peterson\u2019s life didn't begin with the fog and ambition of San Francisco, but in the sun-baked suburbs of Sacramento. Raised by a practical-minded city planner father and a high school teacher mother, his upbringing was one of stability, public schools, and a clear expectation to be self-sufficient. Drawn by the magnetic pull of the first dot-com boom, he moved to the Bay Area for college, earning an economics degree from UC Davis while dreaming of the burgeoning digital world just across the bridge.\n\nHis first foray into tech was a trial by fire. He joined a promising startup in 1999, only to see it evaporate in the 2001 crash. This failure became his most crucial turning point. Humbled and seeking a more strategic foundation, he enrolled at UC Berkeley\u2019s Haas School of Business. The MBA was his reset button, transforming him from a wide-eyed dot-com hopeful into a calculated business leader. His career since has been a steady, methodical climb through the ranks of established tech firms, culminating in his current role as a Director of Product Management, where he guides teams with a calm authority born from experience.\n\nNow 47, David\u2019s life is one of structured comfort. He lives in a meticulously kept condo in NoPa, a neighborhood he chose for its proximity to Golden Gate Park and its vibrant, yet mature, atmosphere. His days begin with a 6 AM run through the Panhandle, followed by coffee from a local cafe before catching the 7:45 AM company shuttle for the short ride to his SOMA office. An amicable divorce five years ago, a mutual decision after he and his ex-wife grew into different people, has left him single. His social life consists of a tight-knit circle of friends, mostly other industry veterans, with whom he shares dinners and weekend trips to wine country.\n\nHe\u2019s seen San Francisco transform and feels a complex connection to it\u2014he\u2019s both a beneficiary and a contributor to the changes he sometimes laments. His future aspirations have shifted from climbing the corporate ladder to achieving more balance. He finds deep satisfaction in mentoring younger product managers but secretly dreams of one day cashing out and opening a small, unpretentious wine bar in Sonoma, leaving the world of product roadmaps and quarterly earnings behind for good."
