            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers the definitive silence of the SoMa office in 2001, taping the final notice to the glass door. The once-vibrant space, with its now-mocking foosball table, was a monument to their collective na\u00efvet\u00e9. The humiliation felt cold and sharp. Walking away that afternoon, he wasn't just leaving a failed startup; he was leaving behind a version of himself. It was the day he swapped blind enthusiasm for deliberate strategy, a lesson that would define his entire career.\n\n2.\nHe was at a Peet\u2019s Coffee in late 2002, compulsively refreshing his email on a clunky laptop. When the subject line \"Congratulations from Berkeley Haas\" appeared, his breath caught. It wasn't just an acceptance letter; it was an anchor. After feeling adrift post-crash, this was proof he could rebuild\u2014this time with a blueprint. That single email represented his second chance, a formal invitation to become the measured, pragmatic man he needed to be.\n\n3.\nThe end of his marriage wasn\u2019t a fight, but a quiet conversation on their NoPa sofa five years ago. They were looking at plans for a kitchen remodel, and he realized they were designing a future for two people who no longer existed. The admission came out without anger, just a deep, shared sadness. Acknowledging the end felt less like a failure and more like respectfully closing a chapter. It taught him that some things, even good things, simply reach their natural conclusion.\n\n4.\nDuring a run through the Panhandle last fall, he saw an old, peeling mural of the \"Summer of Love\" just blocks from a new, glass-walled luxury apartment building. In that single view, he saw the city he\u2019d romanticized and the one he\u2019d helped create. A sharp pang of guilt mixed with a fierce, protective love for the place hit him. He was both the beneficiary and the cause of the change, a contradiction that defined his bittersweet, two-decade relationship with San Francisco.\n\n5.\nTwo years ago, on a dusty patio at a small Sonoma winery, the owner, a man with wine-stained hands, explained the simple challenges of his day. There were no quarterly reviews or product roadmaps, just soil, sun, and grapes. David held a glass of Zinfandel, the afternoon light warming his face, and felt a profound sense of peace he never found in a boardroom. The thought landed then: this felt more like success than anything his tech career could offer."
